            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/s13/800/400', 'title' => 'Neuroplasticity: How the Brain Rewires Itself', 'description' => 'The brain\'s ability to reorganize its structure and function in response to experience, known as neuroplasticity, is far more extensive than scientists believed just two decades ago. New research is leveraging this capacity to treat stroke, addiction, depression, and learning disorders.', 'body' => 'Hebbian plasticity, "neurons that fire together wire together," forms the cellular basis of learning and memory. Structural plasticity allows dendritic spines to form, strengthen, and disappear within hours of intense learning. Non-invasive brain stimulation techniques like transcranial magnetic stimulation can potentiate plasticity windows for therapeutic purposes. The discovery that adult brains continue generating new neurons in the hippocampus overturned a century of established neuroscience.', 'views' => 614, 'categories' => [2]],

