            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p1/800/400', 'title' => 'AI Regulation: Europe Leads, Others Follow', 'description' => 'The EU AI Act represents the world\'s first comprehensive legal framework for artificial intelligence, creating tiered obligations based on risk level. As it enters implementation, other major economies are watching closely and adapting its approach to their own regulatory philosophies.', 'body' => 'The Act prohibits social scoring, real-time biometric surveillance in public spaces, and subliminal manipulation systems. High-risk applications including hiring algorithms, credit scoring, and law enforcement tools face strict transparency and audit requirements. General-purpose AI models above a compute threshold must disclose training data and comply with copyright law. Critics argue the compliance burden disadvantages European AI startups relative to US and Chinese competitors.', 'views' => 678, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p2/800/400', 'title' => 'The Global Water Crisis: Politics of a Scarce Resource', 'description' => 'As climate change accelerates and populations grow, freshwater is becoming the defining geopolitical resource of the 21st century. Transboundary river disputes, aquifer depletion, and infrastructure inequality are creating tensions that threaten both stability and development.', 'body' => 'The Nile basin dispute between Ethiopia, Sudan, and Egypt over the Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam illustrates how water infrastructure can become a source of existential national security concern. The Colorado River compact, designed for a wetter era, now allocates more water than the river contains in dry years. Desalination costs have dropped 90% over thirty years but remain prohibitive for inland populations. Water privatization debates pit efficiency arguments against human rights frameworks with no easy resolution.', 'views' => 543, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p3/800/400', 'title' => 'Electoral Systems Compared: Which Democracy Works Best?', 'description' => 'The choice between first-past-the-post, proportional representation, ranked choice, and mixed systems shapes political outcomes in ways most voters do not recognize. Comparative political science offers increasingly clear evidence about which systems produce the governance outcomes citizens actually want.', 'body' => 'Proportional representation systems produce parliaments that more accurately reflect voter preferences but often require coalition negotiations that delay policy implementation. First-past-the-post creates stable single-party governments at the cost of systematic under-representation of minority viewpoints. Ranked choice voting reduces strategic voting but requires voter education and more complex counting processes. New Zealand\'s transition from FPP to MMP in 1996 provides the closest real-world experiment in direct system comparison.', 'views' => 412, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p4/800/400', 'title' => 'The Future of NATO After Ukraine', 'description' => 'Russia\'s invasion of Ukraine has reshaped European security in ways that will define the continent\'s geopolitical architecture for a generation. NATO\'s enlargement, defense spending commitments, and relationship with non-member partners are all being reconsidered in light of a fundamentally altered threat environment.', 'body' => 'Sweden and Finland\'s accession transformed NATO\'s northern flank, closing the Baltic Sea strategically. European defense spending has increased by an average of 30% since 2022 among member states, with several meeting the 2% GDP commitment for the first time. The debate over European strategic autonomy versus transatlantic dependence has intensified, with differing threat perceptions between Eastern and Western European members creating policy tensions within the alliance.', 'views' => 892, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p5/800/400', 'title' => 'Universal Basic Income: Experiments and Evidence', 'description' => 'Pilot programs for universal basic income have now been conducted in Finland, Kenya, Canada, the United States, and several other countries. The accumulated evidence challenges both enthusiastic predictions and dire warnings, revealing a more nuanced picture than either side anticipated.', 'body' => 'Finland\'s two-year experiment with 2,000 unemployed recipients found improved wellbeing, mental health, and trust in institutions without reducing work participation. GiveDirectly\'s long-running Kenya program demonstrates lasting economic impacts in low-income contexts. Critics point to the funding challenge: universal programs at meaningful income levels require either significant tax increases or reductions in existing targeted benefits. The debate increasingly focuses on targeting versus universality rather than the principle itself.', 'views' => 567, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p6/800/400', 'title' => 'Disinformation and Democracy: The Platform Dilemma', 'description' => 'Social media platforms have become primary information environments for billions of people, creating unprecedented channels for coordinated disinformation campaigns. The challenge of combating false information without enabling censorship is one of the most consequential governance questions of our era.', 'body' => 'Research consistently shows that false information spreads faster and further than corrections on social platforms. Algorithmic amplification of engagement-maximizing content creates structural incentives that disinformation exploits. Labeling false content reduces its spread by approximately 20% in controlled experiments. Prebunking, exposing users to weakened forms of manipulation techniques before they encounter them, shows more durable effects than reactive fact-checking. Platform liability reform debates remain politically deadlocked in most democracies.', 'views' => 734, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p7/800/400', 'title' => 'China\'s Belt and Road Initiative: A Decade of Assessment', 'description' => 'A decade after its announcement, the Belt and Road Initiative has financed infrastructure across 140 countries and created a new architecture of Chinese economic influence. The results are more complex and contested than either Beijing\'s promotional materials or Western critics suggest.', 'body' => 'BRI projects have delivered genuine infrastructure in underserved regions where Western development finance was absent. Debt sustainability concerns are real but unevenly distributed: Sri Lanka\'s Hambantota Port situation has been widely mischaracterized while genuine debt restructuring challenges face several African nations. Chinese contractors\' local employment rates have improved significantly following early criticism. Western alternative frameworks including the G7\'s Partnership for Global Infrastructure have struggled to match BRI\'s speed and risk appetite.', 'views' => 623, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p8/800/400', 'title' => 'The Housing Crisis: Policy Failures and Solutions', 'description' => 'Housing unaffordability has reached crisis levels in major cities across North America, Europe, and Australia, threatening social mobility and economic productivity. The political economy of housing reform explains why effective solutions are technically obvious but politically extraordinarily difficult to implement.', 'body' => 'The core problem in most affected cities is supply restriction: zoning laws, parking minimums, height limits, and lengthy permitting processes systematically prevent housing production from matching demand. Existing homeowners, who vote at higher rates than renters and benefit from property value appreciation, have political incentives to oppose liberalization. Cities that have upzoned substantially, Auckland being the most studied example, show measurable moderation in rent growth relative to comparable restricted markets.', 'views' => 812, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p9/800/400', 'title' => 'Climate Policy: Why Progress Is So Slow', 'description' => 'Despite overwhelming scientific consensus and growing public concern, global greenhouse gas emissions continue rising. Understanding the political economy of climate inaction, from fossil fuel interests to collective action problems and electoral time horizons, is essential for identifying pathways to faster progress.', 'body' => 'Carbon pricing, the policy economists most consistently recommend, faces resistance from industries facing competitive disadvantage if implemented unilaterally and from consumers facing immediate cost increases for diffuse long-term benefits. The fossil fuel industry\'s lobbying expenditure exceeds that of clean energy advocates by a factor of ten in most major democracies. International coordination is complicated by differing development priorities and historical responsibility disputes. Border carbon adjustments offer partial solutions to competitiveness concerns but require complex implementation.', 'views' => 945, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p10/800/400', 'title' => 'Immigration Policy: Evidence vs. Politics', 'description' => 'Immigration is among the most politically contentious issues in Western democracies, yet the empirical evidence on its economic, fiscal, and social impacts is substantially more positive than political discourse suggests. The gap between evidence and policy reflects genuine distributional conflicts and cultural dimensions that economics alone cannot resolve.', 'body' => 'Macroeconomic research consistently finds immigration raises GDP, expands the tax base, and addresses demographic challenges in aging societies. The distributional impacts are heterogeneous: high-skilled immigrants compete more with existing high-skilled workers while providing net fiscal benefits; low-skilled immigrants generate more concentrated competition effects in specific labor markets while using more public services. Crime statistics in virtually every studied context show immigrants commit crimes at lower rates than native-born populations. Cultural anxiety, while not always empirically grounded, represents a real political force requiring engagement beyond dismissal.', 'views' => 1023, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p11/800/400', 'title' => 'The Rise of Technocracy: When Experts Rule', 'description' => 'From central banking to pandemic response to climate policy, complex modern challenges have pushed decision-making authority toward unelected experts. The resulting tension between technocratic effectiveness and democratic accountability is reshaping political institutions across the developed world.', 'body' => 'Central bank independence is the most established example of deliberately insulating consequential economic decisions from electoral pressure. The ECB and Federal Reserve\'s inflation-fighting credibility depends on their perceived freedom from political interference. COVID revealed both the strengths and limits of technocratic governance: scientific consensus on interventions was clear, but trade-off decisions between health, economic, and liberty interests were inherently political. Trust in expertise collapsed in many societies precisely where technocratic governance was most assertive.', 'views' => 534, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p12/800/400', 'title' => 'Tax Havens and Global Minimum Tax: A New Era?', 'description' => 'The OECD\'s global minimum corporate tax agreement, signed by 137 countries, represents the most significant reform of international tax rules in a century. Its implementation is revealing which jurisdictions are genuinely complying and which are finding creative ways to preserve competitive advantages.', 'body' => 'The 15% global minimum rate targets multinationals with revenues above €750 million, covering the majority of large cross-border corporations. Qualifying Domestic Minimum Top-up Taxes allow countries to capture revenue domestically rather than ceding it to parent company jurisdictions. Ireland, despite signing, has structured its implementation to preserve elements of its attractive tax environment. Caribbean and Pacific jurisdictions below the threshold remain outside the agreement\'s reach, maintaining zero-rate options for entities that can restructure below the revenue cutoff.', 'views' => 456, 'categories' => [4]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/p13/800/400', 'title' => 'Youth Movements Reshaping Global Politics', 'description' => 'From climate activism to democracy movements in Southeast Asia, young people are driving political change in ways that established institutions are struggling to understand or accommodate. The combination of digital organizing tools and genuine intergenerational grievances is creating a distinctive political force.', 'body' => 'Fridays for Future mobilized millions of young people across 150 countries without conventional organizational infrastructure, demonstrating social media\'s capacity to coordinate decentralized movements. Youth voter turnout has increased significantly in multiple countries following the pandemic, shifting electoral calculations for parties that previously discounted this demographic. The intergenerational equity dimension of climate, housing, and pension policy is creating political alignments that cut across traditional left-right dimensions.', 'views' => 678, 'categories' => [4]],

            // Culture (5)
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c1/800/400', 'title' => 'Streaming Wars: How Netflix Changed Everything', 'description' => 'Netflix\'s transformation from DVD postal service to global entertainment empire triggered a competitive response that has restructured the entire media industry, producing both a golden age of television and a consolidation crisis that is eliminating the mid-budget projects that once defined Hollywood.', 'body' => 'The streaming model\'s original advantage was subscriber growth funded by debt, enabling content investment that traditional broadcast economics couldn\'t match. As subscriber growth saturated developed markets, profitability pressure has produced password-sharing crackdowns, ad-supported tiers, and content budget reductions that mirror the network television model streaming supposedly disrupted. The consolidation of Paramount+, Max, and Peacock reflects an industry recognizing that fragmentation has reached consumer tolerance limits.', 'views' => 892, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c2/800/400', 'title' => 'The Vinyl Revival: Why Records Are Back', 'description' => 'Vinyl record sales have increased for eighteen consecutive years, with revenue now exceeding CDs for the first time since 1987. The reasons behind this counterintuitive trend reveal something important about how people relate to music in an age of infinite digital abundance.', 'body' => 'Vinyl\'s resurgence cannot be explained solely by audiophile arguments about sound quality, since most buyers play records through systems that don\'t reveal the format\'s technical advantages over high-quality digital streaming. Ownership psychology, album artwork as physical object, ritual of side-flipping, and collector community dynamics all play documented roles. Artists benefit from significantly higher per-unit revenue than streaming, creating aligned incentives. The format\'s scarcity and fragility paradoxically enhance its perceived value.', 'views' => 567, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c3/800/400', 'title' => 'K-Pop\'s Global Conquest: Beyond BTS', 'description' => 'BTS proved that non-English language music could achieve genuine global commercial dominance, but the K-Pop industry\'s systematic approach to developing internationally marketable artists suggests the phenomenon is structural rather than contingent on any individual act\'s exceptional qualities.', 'body' => 'K-Pop\'s idol system involves years of intensive training in singing, dance, language, and fan interaction before debut, producing performers of extraordinary technical consistency. HYBE, SM, YG, and JYP have developed production systems that create music specifically engineered for cross-cultural appeal, with English phrases embedded strategically and choreography optimized for short-form video platforms. Fan engagement mechanics, including regular live streams, fan meetings, and elaborate merchandise ecosystems, generate revenue that Western artist models largely forgo.', 'views' => 734, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c4/800/400', 'title' => 'The Museum of the Future: Art in the Digital Age', 'description' => 'Museums are grappling with digitization, NFT controversies, decolonization demands, and the challenge of engaging younger audiences who experience art primarily through screens. How institutions navigate these pressures will determine whether the museum remains culturally central or becomes a niche destination.', 'body' => 'The British Museum\'s repatriation debates and the Louvre\'s Abu Dhabi satellite illustrate how cultural institutions are simultaneously pulled toward cosmopolitan universalism and national/cultural specificity. Digital collection access initiatives have dramatically expanded reach while raising questions about whether virtual access substitutes for or stimulates physical attendance. Immersive art experiences like teamLab and Meow Wolf attract demographics that traditional fine art museums struggle to reach, suggesting appetite for experiential art engagement that the medium of painting alone cannot satisfy.', 'views' => 423, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c5/800/400', 'title' => 'Architecture for Climate: Building for an Uncertain Future', 'description' => 'Climate change is forcing architects to fundamentally reconsider how buildings are designed, built, and operated. The sector responsible for 39% of global carbon emissions is undergoing its most significant reorientation since the modernist movement, driven by regulation, client demand, and the profession\'s own awakening to its responsibility.', 'body' => 'Embodied carbon, the emissions from materials production and construction itself, has received far less attention than operational energy efficiency despite comprising roughly half of a new building\'s lifetime carbon impact. Mass timber construction dramatically reduces embodied carbon while providing renewable structural material. Passive house standards achieve 90% heating energy reduction through envelope optimization, eliminating fossil fuel dependency without active systems. The challenge of retrofitting the existing building stock represents a far larger problem than new construction.', 'views' => 356, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c6/800/400', 'title' => 'Literature in the Age of AI: Creativity Under Pressure', 'description' => 'Generative AI\'s ability to produce plausible prose at scale is forcing the literary world to confront fundamental questions about authorship, originality, and what human creative expression offers that machine generation cannot replicate. The answers are revealing as much about our assumptions as about the technology itself.', 'body' => 'Publishers have begun requiring disclosure of AI assistance in submitted manuscripts, while simultaneously exploring AI for cover design, marketing copy, and translation. The science fiction and romance genres, with their formulaic elements, face greater disruption than literary fiction whose market values idiosyncratic voice. Writers argue that the process of writing, the struggle, revision, and discovery, is integral to the work\'s meaning in ways that output quality alone cannot capture. The legal status of training data and AI-generated content copyright remains unresolved in most jurisdictions.', 'views' => 789, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c7/800/400', 'title' => 'Food as Culture: The Politics of Cuisine', 'description' => 'Culinary traditions carry identity, history, and power in ways that extend far beyond nutrition. The global spread of food cultures, debates over cultural appropriation in restaurants, and the politics of UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage designations reveal how much is at stake when we talk about what people eat.', 'body' => 'Japan\'s successful campaign to register washoku as UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage generated billions in food tourism. Mexico and Peru have built national identity strategies significantly around culinary distinction. The appropriation debate pits concerns about exploitation and misrepresentation against arguments that cultural exchange is how cuisine evolves and spreads. Gentrification\'s impact on ethnic food neighborhoods often follows a pattern: increased visibility and prestige accompanied by displacement of the communities whose cuisine is being celebrated.', 'views' => 512, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c8/800/400', 'title' => 'The Podcast Boom and the Audio Renaissance', 'description' => 'Podcasting has matured from a hobbyist medium into a multi-billion dollar industry that is now experiencing its own consolidation and professionalization challenges. The intimacy of audio storytelling has proven extraordinarily durable in a visual-first media environment.', 'body' => 'Spotify\'s $1 billion podcast acquisition spree between 2019 and 2022 demonstrated major platform conviction in the medium\'s commercial potential, though many of those acquisitions have since been wound down as profitability replaced growth as the primary metric. True crime\'s sustained dominance reveals deep audience appetite for narrative journalism that engages moral intuition. The shift from download-based to streaming measurement has produced dramatically different audience numbers that complicate advertising market maturation.', 'views' => 445, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c9/800/400', 'title' => 'Video Games as Art: The Medium Comes of Age', 'description' => 'From Disco Elysium\'s literary ambition to The Last of Us\'s emotional storytelling, video games are increasingly achieving the cultural recognition and critical apparatus previously reserved for film and literature. The medium\'s unique property of player agency creates artistic possibilities no other medium can replicate.', 'body' => 'Games like Spec Ops: The Line use player agency to implicate the audience in violence that film can only observe, creating ethical experiences impossible in passive media. The roguelike genre\'s embrace of repetition and death as meaningful mechanical elements turns failure into a form of storytelling. Indie development has democratized production to the point where a single developer can create commercially and critically successful work, paralleling independent cinema\'s relationship to Hollywood. BAFTA and The Game Awards\' expanding critical prestige signals institutional recognition.', 'views' => 678, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c10/800/400', 'title' => 'Fashion\'s Sustainability Crisis', 'description' => 'Fast fashion\'s environmental footprint, from water consumption and chemical pollution to textile waste mountains in Ghana and Chile, has made the apparel industry one of the most scrutinized sectors in corporate sustainability debates. The gap between brand commitments and actual impact reduction remains substantial.', 'body' => 'The fashion industry produces 92 million tonnes of textile waste annually. Polyester, comprising 54% of fiber production, is derived from fossil fuels and sheds microplastics with each wash. Greenwashing investigations have found that the majority of sustainability claims made by major fast fashion brands fail independent verification standards. The resale market, growing at three times the rate of primary apparel, represents genuine circular economy progress, though its growth may increase total consumption by making fashion more affordable overall.', 'views' => 534, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c11/800/400', 'title' => 'The Return of the Cinema: Post-Pandemic Lessons', 'description' => 'Hollywood\'s bet that theatrical exclusivity could coexist with streaming has produced mixed results, with blockbusters performing strongly while mid-budget films struggle to find theatrical audiences willing to leave home. The cinema industry\'s survival strategy is emerging from the data of four post-pandemic years.', 'body' => 'The theatrical window has stabilized at approximately 45 days, down from the traditional 90, with evidence that shorter windows actually increase rather than decrease theatrical revenue for most titles. Premium large-format auditoriums generate disproportionate revenue and attract the social event-driven attendance that streaming cannot replicate. The studios and theaters that have survived are those that recognized cinema\'s competitive advantage is the shared experience rather than content exclusivity, and have invested accordingly in presentation quality and programming curation.', 'views' => 623, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c12/800/400', 'title' => 'Dance Music\'s Cultural Geography', 'description' => 'Electronic dance music\'s global spread has produced regional scenes with distinctive aesthetics rooted in specific urban and cultural contexts. From Chicago house and Detroit techno\'s origins in Black LGBTQ communities to Afrobeats\' Atlantic crossing and Amapiano\'s South African emergence, the geography of dance music is inseparable from the social history of its creators.', 'body' => 'Chicago house emerged from the post-disco underground club scene in a city experiencing deindustrialization and racial segregation, with Frankie Knuckles and Larry Heard creating music from available technology for communities excluded from mainstream entertainment. Amapiano\'s international breakthrough, driven by social media dance challenges, represents the first major South African music genre to achieve global commercial scale independently of Western label infrastructure. The economic returns from dance music\'s globalization have historically been captured far more by distributors and promoters than by originating communities.', 'views' => 412, 'categories' => [5]],
            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c13/800/400', 'title' => 'The Graphic Novel Grows Up', 'description' => 'From Art Spiegelman\'s Maus to Marjane Satrapi\'s Persepolis to Alison Bechdel\'s Fun Home, literary graphic novels have achieved critical prestige, academic study, and mainstream publishing investment that the medium\'s founders could not have anticipated. The form\'s unique combination of word and image continues to attract writers and artists seeking to do things neither can do alone.', 'body' => 'The graphic novel\'s commercial and critical maturation has produced a diversity of voices that mainstream prose publishing has struggled to match. Autobiographical work dominates literary graphic novels because the form\'s visual specificity makes personal experience particularly immediate. Chris Ware\'s structural experimentation pushes the form\'s page-as-architectural-space possibilities in ways that no other medium can replicate. Library and educational adoption has created stable non-bookstore sales channels that sustain authors through slower commercial periods.', 'views' => 378, 'categories' => [5]],
        

            ['image' => 'https://picsum.photos/seed/c1/800/400', 'title' => 'test', 'description' => 'test', 'body' => 'The streaming model\'s original advantage was subscriber growth funded by debt, enabling content investment that traditional broadcast economics couldn\'t match. As subscriber growth saturated developed markets, profitability pressure has produced password-sharing crackdowns, ad-supported tiers, and content budget reductions that mirror the network television model streaming supposedly disrupted. The consolidation of Paramount+, Max, and Peacock reflects an industry recognizing that fragmentation has reached consumer tolerance limits.', 'views' => 892, 'categories' => [6]],
